{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Proposal questions are answerable immediately, enabling execution before the referenced governance vote ends","locations":["onchain_auto/0x8f9036732b9aa9b82d8f35e54b71faeb2f573e2f/contracts/DaoModule.sol:176","onchain_auto/0x8f9036732b9aa9b82d8f35e54b71faeb2f573e2f/contracts/DaoModule.sol:177","onchain_auto/0x8f9036732b9aa9b82d8f35e54b71faeb2f573e2f/contracts/DaoModule.sol:181","onchain_auto/0x8f9036732b9aa9b82d8f35e54b71faeb2f573e2f/contracts/DaoModule.sol:182","onchain_auto/0x8f9036732b9aa9b82d8f35e54b71faeb2f573e2f/contracts/interfaces/Realitio.sol:17","onchain_auto/0x8f9036732b9aa9b82d8f35e54b71faeb2f573e2f/contracts/interfaces/Realitio.sol:20"],"claim":"`addProposalWithNonce` always computes and asks the Realitio question with `openingTs/opening_ts = 0`, and the code even documents that this makes the question immediately answerable. Because anyone can call `addProposal`/`addProposalWithNonce`, an attacker can open the oracle question and start the timeout/cooldown clock before the underlying off-chain governance process has actually concluded.","impact":"A malicious actor can front-run an in-flight governance proposal, get a premature `YES` finalized, and execute the committed Safe transaction bundle before the real vote has ended or before its true outcome is known. Even when honest users later try to submit the official question, the duplicate submission path is already occupied, creating a governance-layer race and potential early execution of unauthorized actions.","paths":["Attacker identifies a pending off-chain proposal and the transaction bundle that governance is expected to approve.","Attacker calls `addProposal` or `addProposalWithNonce` before the off-chain vote end time.","Because `opening_ts` is hardcoded to `0`, the oracle question can be answered immediately and finalized after `questionTimeout` plus `questionCooldown`.","Once finalized with `YES`, anyone can call `executeProposalWithIndex` and execute the transactions even though the referenced governance vote was still ongoing or later failed."] ,"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Expiring approvals can permanently strand multi-transaction proposals in a partially executed state","locations":["onchain_auto/0x8f9036732b9aa9b82d8f35e54b71faeb2f573e2f/contracts/DaoModule.sol:167","onchain_auto/0x8f9036732b9aa9b82d8f35e54b71faeb2f573e2f/contracts/DaoModule.sol:171","onchain_auto/0x8f9036732b9aa9b82d8f35e54b71faeb2f573e2f/contracts/DaoModule.sol:172","onchain_auto/0x8f9036732b9aa9b82d8f35e54b71faeb2f573e2f/contracts/DaoModule.sol:215","onchain_auto/0x8f9036732b9aa9b82d8f35e54b71faeb2f573e2f/contracts/DaoModule.sol:220","onchain_auto/0x8f9036732b9aa9b82d8f35e54b71faeb2f573e2f/contracts/DaoModule.sol:223","onchain_auto/0x8f9036732b9aa9b82d8f35e54b71faeb2f573e2f/contracts/DaoModule.sol:264","onchain_auto/0x8f9036732b9aa9b82d8f35e54b71faeb2f573e2f/contracts/DaoModule.sol:266","onchain_auto/0x8f9036732b9aa9b82d8f35e54b71faeb2f573e2f/contracts/DaoModule.sol:268"],"claim":"The module executes proposal transactions one index at a time and enforces ordered execution, but each execution also requires the oracle `YES` answer to remain within `answerExpiration`. If only a prefix is executed before expiration, later indices become unexecutable. Re-asking the proposal is also blocked unless the prior oracle result itself equals `INVALIDATED`; a merely expired positive answer does not satisfy that condition, and the helper that marks expired answers as invalid writes the internal sentinel `INVALIDATED`, which also blocks nonce-based resubmission.","impact":"An attacker can wait until the end of the validity window, execute only the favorable prefix of a multi-step upgrade or migration, and then let the approval expire. The remaining calls become permanently stuck, leaving the protocol in a half-executed state that can lock funds, break invariants, or strand upgrades/migrations without a recovery path through the same proposal payload.","paths":["Governance approves a proposal containing multiple ordered transactions.","An attacker waits until shortly before `answerExpiration` and executes transaction index `0` or another early prefix.","After the answer expires, later `executeProposalWithIndex` calls revert with `Answer has expired`, while ordered execution prevents skipping ahead.","The same proposal cannot be cleanly resubmitted through `addProposalWithNonce`, because nonce-based retry only accepts a prior oracle result of `INVALIDATED`, and the module's own expired-answer cleanup instead stores the internal `INVALIDATED` sentinel that the retry path explicitly rejects."] ,"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Minimum-bond enforcement checks the highest historical bond, not the winning answer's backing","locations":["onchain_auto/0x8f9036732b9aa9b82d8f35e54b71faeb2f573e2f/contracts/DaoModule.sol:259","onchain_auto/0x8f9036732b9aa9b82d8f35e54b71faeb2f573e2f/contracts/DaoModule.sol:260","onchain_auto/0x8f9036732b9aa9b82d8f35e54b71faeb2f573e2f/contracts/DaoModule.sol:261","onchain_auto/0x8f9036732b9aa9b82d8f35e54b71faeb2f573e2f/contracts/interfaces/Realitio.sol:47","onchain_auto/0x8f9036732b9aa9b82d8f35e54b71faeb2f573e2f/contracts/interfaces/Realitio.sol:48"],"claim":"`executeProposalWithIndex` treats `minimumBond` as a guard on the accepted oracle answer, but it validates the threshold with `oracle.getBond(questionId)`. The interface explicitly defines this value as the highest bond ever posted for the question, regardless of whether that bond backs the answer that ultimately wins.","impact":"A proposal can satisfy the module's bond threshold even when the final `YES` answer is not economically backed by that amount, especially after disputes or arbitration. This weakens the intended anti-manipulation guarantee of `minimumBond` and can let a lower-security or externally imposed final answer unlock proposal execution.","paths":["A large bond is posted at some point on a competing or losing answer, pushing `getBond(questionId)` above `minimumBond`.","The final winning answer later becomes `YES` through a path that does not preserve that same economic backing, such as arbitration.","The module checks only `getBond(questionId) >= minimumBond` and therefore accepts execution even though the winning answer itself was never secured by the configured minimum bond."] ,"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"The oracle question hides the executable payload behind opaque hashes instead of human-verifiable call data","source_agents":["codex_1"],"reason":"The contract cryptographically commits to the exact transaction preimages via `txHashes`; an attacker cannot swap in different calldata at execution time without changing the committed hashes. This is more a governance/UX visibility concern than a concrete protocol bug in the module."},{"title":"DelegateCall allows arbitrary code execution in DaoModule context","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Arbitrary proposal execution, including `DelegateCall`, is an intended capability of a Safe-style executor once governance/oracle approval is obtained. This is part of the module's trust model, not a distinct implementation flaw; the call also executes through the executor rather than granting new standalone authority to arbitrary callers."},{"title":"No bounds check on txIndex allows out-of-bounds array access","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"An invalid `txIndex` only reverts that specific caller's transaction. It does not block valid executions or create a persistent denial of service because honest users can still supply a correct index."},{"title":"No validation that target address is non-zero","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The proposal payload is intentionally arbitrary and already cryptographically committed. Sending to `address(0)` would require an approved proposal and is a governance choice, not an unintended exploit path introduced by the module."},{"title":"Arbitrary target address allows any contract interaction","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is the core purpose of a governance execution module: execute arbitrary approved calls via the executor. Without a separate approval bypass, unrestricted targets are not a vulnerability by themselves."},{"title":"Oracle dependency is single point of failure for security","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Reliance on Realitio/arbitration is an explicit trust assumption of the design, not a bug in this implementation."},{"title":"No validation on value parameter in executeProposal","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"If the executor lacks sufficient balance, the call simply reverts. That does not create a new exploit beyond governance approving an unexecutable transaction."},{"title":"Minimum bond check uses <= instead of >=","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`minBond == 0 || minBond <= oracle.getBond(questionId)` is the correct comparison for enforcing a minimum threshold. Allowing `minimumBond` to be set to zero is an explicit configuration choice by the executor, not a coding error."}]}
